05123nam a22006015i 9780520939271DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20042004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209392717 a10.1525/97805209392712doi  a(DE-B1597)520590  a(OCoLC)55538489  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJV6483b.D69 2004eb 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a365/.42221 aDow, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Gulag :bInside U.S. Immigration Prisons /cMark Dow. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (426 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPrologue: "Let This Be Home" -- t1. Invisibility, Intimidation, and the INS -- t2. September 11: Secrecy, Disruption, and Continuity -- t3. Another World, Another Nation: Miami's Krome Detention Center -- t4. "Enforcement Means You're Brutal" -- t5. The World's First Private Prison -- t6. "Keeping Quiet Means Deny": A Hunger Strike in Queens -- t7. The Art of Jailing -- t8. "Criminal Aliens" and Criminal Agents -- t9. Siege, Shackles, Climate, Design -- t10. "Speak to Every Media": Resistance, Repression, and the Making of a Prisoner -- t11. Good and Evil in New England -- t12. Out West: Philosophy and Despair -- t13. Dead Time -- t14. Mariel Cubans: Abandoned, Again and Again -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore September 11, 2001, few Americans had heard of immigration detention, but in fact a secret and repressive prison system run by the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service has existed in this country for more than two decades. In American Gulag, prisoners, jailers, and whistle-blowing federal officials come forward to describe the frightening reality inside these INS facilities. Journalist Mark Dow's on-the-ground reporting brings to light documented cases of illegal beatings and psychological torment, prolonged detention, racism, and inhumane conditions. Intelligent, impassioned, and unlike anything that has been written on the topic, this gripping work of investigative journalism should be read by all Americans. It is a book that will change the way we see our country. American Gulag takes us inside prisons such as the Krome North Service Processing Center in Miami, the Corrections Corporation of America's Houston Processing Center, and county jails around the country that profit from contracts to hold INS prisoners. It contains disturbing in-depth profiles of detainees, including Emmy Kutesa, a defector from the Ugandan army who was tortured and then escaped to the United States, where he was imprisoned in Queens, and then undertook a hunger strike in protest. To provide a framework for understanding stories like these, Dow gives a brief history of immigration laws and practices in the United States-including the repercussions of September 11 and present-day policies. His book reveals that current immigration detentions are best understood not as a well-intentioned response to terrorism but rather as part of the larger context of INS secrecy and excessive authority. American Gulag exposes the full story of a cruel prison system that is operating today with an astonishing lack of accountability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAlien detention centersxUnited States. 0aAlien detention centerszUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawxUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aHuman rightsxUnited States. 0aHuman rightszUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIE